Review: Cinematically boring and uninspired, narratively brilliant and subtle. You can tell it was re-engineered in the editing room a bit but, despite the hand of the director being faintly seen, the hand of the writer is bold and incisive.

This is pure performance candy. I hope Todd Haynes feels like he’s allowed to die now knowing he’s put two of the most exceptional performances of the decade to film. And even beyond Portman and Moore, the supporting cast here is unbelievable. The husband carries so much of the weight of this film.
Everything’s about incels and stuff these days, huh?

Good lord the Japanese sure know how to invoke the power of God. The score in this movie simply does not quit my friends. Choirs upon choirs regale us as we bask in the destructive delights of the one and only Godzilla.
This sincerely devastates me to say, but I didn’t like this movie. I cried afterward because I didn’t like it.

Possibly the best film I've seen in the last 5 years. I need to see it again before I can really articulate why but, suffice to say, few films I have seen match form to content so perfectly, and even fewer are quite as intentionally withholding (in a way only film can be) to such extraordinary, transcendent effect. Devastating, incredible, not about what you think it's about.
The OGs of games were true bleeding edge artists, people who turn their nose up at this shit are luddites.
Forgettable enough that I’m logging it 1 month later.
One of the greatest of all time.
I really didn’t like this minus some shots

Capitalism wins. No but really, for what this is it’s pretty good. It goes over the top at parts but games are fascinating and the game business is fascinating and this movie is filled with shockingly good performances and we’ll paced edits. A great watch and a pretty nuts story.
Small joys, little sorrows. Temporal atmosphere.
